"The sea belongs to us": a landlocked Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
Sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings, navy blue flags fly.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases bear the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
Getting it back is a duty.”
Throughout Bolivia, a land without a sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the yearning to return to sailing the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the highest in decades, as Bolivia expects an International Court of Justice resolution on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the International Court of Justice’s ruling on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, who is waging a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has a lot to say about Monday’s resolution.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to allocate Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s decision comes just six months after the final pleadings indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
Far from promoting Bolivia’s cause, it may have been numbed in the last four years.
"The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zarate said.
In addition, he suggested that Morales’ belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to speak at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodr<0xC3><0xAD>guez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making was unusually rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and the possibility of “putting an end to 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
