There are more than 820,000 people affected in the country, according to health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually infected, which is a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly through parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who contract HIV in this way has been reduced by almost all, Chinese health authorities said at a congress held in Yunnan province.
Every year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGBT group suffers a lot of discrimination.
Because of the country’s conservative values, studies have estimated that between 70 and 90 percent of men who have sex with other men will end up marrying women.
Many transmissions of diseases are due to not using adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, China’s government has pledged universal access to HIV medicines as part of an attempt to address the problem.
