The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been conducted in a state in the Scottish Highlands, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything found is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as river bats from Daubenton and long-eared browns from the Inverewe Gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile research with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of bat calls and what species do.
A report and a map of the habitat will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
Because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts in the field, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated Scotland’s first and only bat reserve in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The property’s director, David Thompson, says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a fantastic bat zone,” he said.
“We have old buildings, many old trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still a lot unknown about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, as a breeding colony can be inadvertently destroyed and 400 females and young could be killed, which would annihilate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
